Message.Msg: "6 milion more jobs" Really! Try this: Huff Post Fact Check, Feb. 13, 2013 "OBAMA: "After years of grueling recession, our businesses have created over 6 million new jobs." THE FACTS: That's in the ballpark, as far as it goes. But Obama starts his count not when he took office, but from the point in his first term when job losses were the highest. In doing so, he ignores the 5 million or so jobs that were lost on his watch, up to that point. Private sector jobs have grown by 6.1 million since February 2010. But since he became president, the gain is a more modest 1.9 million. And when losses in public sector employment are added to the mix, his overall jobs record is a gain of 1.2 million." Somehow I'm not smelling the same roses you are. As I said earlier, a dumbed down America.

Topic.Title: After the landslide vote in November, are the American people starting to suffer from buyers remorse?

Message.Msg: That all depends on how you present the numbers. Were they new jobs? Were they simply rehires of those that lost their jobs in the last four years? Were they all low paying jobs and the reason behind his push for the increase in the minimum wage? Most of the 'fact' checker sites; both liberal and conservative have expressed doubts around the legitimacy of that number and many others of his claims, like the increase in mileage being doubled since he came into office. His claims of the successes of the ‘green’ energy efforts he touts are deceptive at best and an outlandish lie typically. They can present the UE numbers anyway they want, the fact remains is that there are more people out of work today than any time in our history and certainly since he took office. He has failed at nearly every campaign promise and he refuses to lead, only to campaign forever. Why, when our economy is still failing does he need to fly all around the country to give a speech that most don't believe anyway? Why can't he make those same speeches from Washington? Does he not understand the philosophy of unnecessary spending and conserving what bits of the nation’s treasury he can? Housing prices are increasing but people still don’t have jobs to afford a home. He wants to find new ways to get voters into homes…the Democratic Party efforts to increase home ownership in the past is a large part of the reason for our current economic conditions. Does he want to repeat those? My God why? His speech last night was full of factual errors, highflying political platitudes and empty promises and call for more spending. He could be successful without revising the tax codes if he were smart...we don't need more taxes, we need more taxpayers.
Gee, where have we heard that campaign promise before? Oh yeah, a little over four years ago. My how time flies when you down and out.

He learned that dime thing from Bill Clinton. It is a true statement but 99% of people don't analyze what is being said. I turned his speech off after about 5 minutes. I couldn't stand all those idiots clapping every time he told another lie.

No chart believers on this board?? I make one or two hundred dollars a day with only a $4,000 investment by watching the charts on AT&T. A month ago I only had $2,000. I use the weekly options and don't win them all but enough to average over $100 a day. I figure that if I double my money every month for a year I will have 16 Billion, less taxes. Well, if I can just get back the $300,000 I have lost in the stock market I will be happy; and it will be tax free.
I don't know about charts but I know $35.60 is a brick wall for this stock.

$35.81 was the high today and I sold 35.5 calls for 30 cents and bought them back for 20 cents. Had I been more patient I could have bought them back for 9 cents now. I don't usually trade in and out in the same day because, if you do it three times in a week they lock up your account. Day trading requires at least $25,000. I don't expect T to go above $36 until after a pull back to near $34. but I expect to be above $36 by the end of the month.

He says we can't cut our way to prosperity. We can't spend our way to prosperity either, particularly when we will soon be struggling to pay the interest on the money we have already overspent. Most of his plans call for increased spending. How can he claim it won't cost anymore? What he means is that it won't cost anymore than he has already planned to spend. Just another political shell game and he thinks we aren't smart enough to see it. He may be correct because collectively we haven't been smart enough to stop it.
